aw and using the wrong calculation.<br><br>N = 23<br>#comparisons = [N*(N - 1)]\/2] = 253<br>P of any two ppl not having same bday = (364\/365)<br>Total P of no 2 ppl, out of 23, having same bday = (364\/365)^253 = .499<br>Total P of any 2 ppl, out of 23, having same bday = 1 - above &gt; 50%","time":1493341182,"resto":123119597,"id":"lvyzPOGJ","country":"US","country_name":"United States"},{"no":123121487,"now":"04\/27\/17(Thu)21:08:19","name":"Anonymous","com":"<a href=\"#p123120452\" class=\"quotelink\">&gt;&gt;123120452<\/a><br><br>Think of it like this: what is the probability that adding person number N will give you a birthday collision?<br><br>If it&#039;s one person, obviously P(1) = 0.<br><br>If it&#039;s two, then it&#039;s P(2) = 1\/365<br><br>If it&#039;s three, the first two couldn&#039;t have a collision (since P(2) would have gotten it). However there are 2 people the third person can match with. P(3) = (1-P(2)) * 2\/365<br><br>P(4) = (1-P(3)) * 3\/365<br><br>Summing P(2) up to P(N) gives you the probability that there of any two sharing a birthday with N people. You can do this in Excel or write a recursive program. HTH<br><br>You might like Project Euler, btw. Lot&#039;s of problems like this. Some harder, some easier.","time":1493341699,"resto":123119597,"id":"trY5cWb6","country":"US","country_name":"United States"},{"no":123121949,"now":"04\/27\/17(Thu)21:12:06","name":"Anonymous","com":"<a href=\"#p123121487\" class=\"quotelink\">&gt;&gt;123121487<\/a><br>I&#039;ll have to look into Project Euler. I kind of get the Bday paradox now, but only in hindsight. Never would have thought of it appropriately before hand. Gives a new perspective on problems going forth though.<br><br>Tooting my own horn though, I did correctly answer the Monty Hall problem first time asked.","time":1493341926,"resto":123119597,"id":"lvyzPOGJ","country":"US","country_name":"United States"},{"no":123123016,"now":"04\/27\/17(Thu)21:21:06","name":"Anonymous","com":"<a href=\"